By using the identity $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{2} \sin 2 \theta / \sin \theta$ repeatedly, we obtain

$$
T = \left(\frac{\sin \left(2^{s} \varphi\right)}{2^{s} \sin \varphi}\right)^{2}
$$

Due to the periodicity of trigonometric functions, we know $T(\varphi) = T(\varphi + \pi)$. When the light transmittance is at maximum, we have $\varphi = p \pi$, where $p$ is an integer. Solving for maximum transmittance $2^{s} \varphi = \pi$ and minimum transmittance $2^{s}(\varphi + \delta \varphi) = 2 \pi$, we find the half-width of transmittance $\delta \varphi = \pi / 2^{s}$. In terms of wavelength, when the transmittance is at maximum,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\varphi &= \left(n_{x} - n_{y}\right) k d / 2 = p \pi \\
\delta \varphi &= \pi \delta p = \pi / 2^{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus

$$
\begin{aligned}
\delta p &= 1 / 2^{s} \\
\lambda &= \left(n_{x} - n_{y}\right) d / p \\
\delta \lambda &= \left|\frac{\left(n_{x} - n_{y}\right) d}{p^{2}} \delta p\right|
\end{aligned}
$$

The relative bandwidth of the transmittance wavelength is

$$
\frac{\delta \lambda}{\lambda} = \frac{2}{p 2^{s}} = \frac{1}{p 2^{s-1}}
$$

